deck: A demon who setup his own miniature hell in California
description:
Origin

Beroul is a demon, he gained the attention of John Constantine by trapping the soul of a girl who was related to a friend of his, drawing the magic user and demon slayer to California where the demon has made his own miniature hell.

He seeks John's assistance to drive out competition (other demons) and to grow his hell into more than what it already is.

Creation

Beroul first appears in Hellblazer: All His Engines and was created by Mike Carey and Leonardo Manco.

Powers & Abilities

Beroul possesses a human form but it has long since lost all but the most basic of human traits and the body can be used for his powers. When eating, John asks if it is alright if he smokes and Beroul tells him "all the cancer tissue is used in this body". Despite his powers and longevity, he is not immortal as John used a death god to destroy Beroul's opponents, so he can die. Beroul possesses divine (though demonic) powers and can trap a human soul in a single cell in his body. He can shapeshift and possesses super strength. He also possesses great knowledge.
name: Beroul

deck: A mysterious villain whom hates Spider-Man and Deadpool for some unknown reason. He is alos the creator of Itsy Bitsy
description:
Origin

Not much is known about Patient Zero, not even his true name. Fact is that he truly hates Spider-Man and Deadpool for some unknown reason.

Creation

Patient Zero was created by Joe kelly and Ed McGuinness and first appeared in Appearance Spider-Man/Deadpool issue 8 (2016).

Major Story Arcs

Vendetta

As his anger towards Spider-Man and Deadpool grew, Patient Zero started kidnapping and ecsperamenting on homeless people. He eventually hired Deadpool and tricked him into killing Peter Parker. When Deadpool realised he was tricked, he managed to bring Peter Parker back to life and attacked Patient Zero. He was furious that the did not know who he was.
name: Patient Zero

deck: A woman whom was a test-subject of Patient Zero. She received DNA from both Spider-Man and Deadpool, which caused her to turn into a spider-like psycotic creature.
description:
Origin

Isty Bitsy's past is mostly unknown. She revealed her name to be Susan Mary, but it is unknown whether this is true. She became a test-subject of the mysterious "Patient Zero", whom gave her DNA from both Spider-Man and Deadpool. As such, she soon begain to mutate.

Creation

Itsy Bitsy was created by Joe Kelly and Ed McGuinnes and first appeared (in human form) in Spider-Man/Deadpool issue 8 (2016). She first appeared as Itsy Bitsy one issue later in Spider-Man/Deadpool issue 9 (2016).

Major Story Arcs

A hero?

When Itsy Bitsy gained her powers, she was tasked by Patient Zero to kill Spider-Man and Deadpool. At first she worked along, following the two heroes. She even assisted them in taking out and even killing a group of villains whom they where fighting. Spider-Man and Deadpool where horrified and tried to stop. Itsy Bitsy then flead the scene. Something however whent wrong, as she turned against her maker afterwards. Her maker fled but was eventually killed by Itsy Bitsy when he asked Spider-Man and Deadpool for help. She told them that she wanted to become a hero and kill the sinners. Obvious to both Spider-Man and Deadpool, Itsy Bitsy was psycotic and they both tried to take her down.
name: Itsy Bitsy

deck: Villain created by The Master (Robby Reed).
description:
Creation

Arsenal was created by fan Roger Banham, of Whitehall, North Carolina for the Adventure Comics run of "Dial 'H' For Hero." This run existed on the shoulders of a contest for readers to send in their own creations to be featured in the comic. Arsenal was likely tweaked and made ready for comics by Carmine Infantino and Marv Wolfman. He was introduced as one of the Evil Eight. The name was later reused by DC as an alias for Roy Harper.

Origin

It wasn't truly explained until the end of the series, but Arsenal was created by The Master- an evil persona of original Dialer Robby Reed. When wrapping up the Dial "H" For Hero run in the back pages of New Adventures of Superboy, it was revealed that villains that failed The Master were consigned to a disintegration pit. Even though the terms of the contest submissions stipulated that DC owned any characters submitted, the disintegration pit insured that the characters would not appear again. However, in the 2012 Dial H series, it has been revealed that dialed personas exist in alternate universes. It could reasonably be assumed that the villains exist also, and could one day reappear in the DCU.
name: Arsenal
